Full disclosure: I did fairly well on the LSAT almost 40 years ago. But it was the most miserable test-taking experience of my life.

@Eric Hougland
I’m curious to hear how much it costs to take the LSAT nowadays.  When I wrote it some 48 years ago, it cost a whopping $35.  Why did I choose law as a career, having started out as a public servant for the federal government?  My wife persuaded me, on having scored as high as I did, that it would be a shame to waste all that money and not apply to a law school to see if I could get in.

(Anyone else care to share their interesting story about having switched careers, whether for law or anything else?)

@Adam H I agree the answer was easy to deduce, but the clue wasn’t accurately composed. 

Nobody ever says that they have “passed” the LSAT. They just get a score. In contrast to the bar exam — which one generally must pass to practice law — the LSAT score merely helps to determine which schools are likely options. No score is too high or too low to go to law school or become a lawyer.

I realize I’m being stupidly pedantic. This tiny error didn’t at all detract from my puzzle experience. I just thought it’d add my 2-cents because I noodled the same question as I was solving it.

